1-Load the healthy training segments and the test windows (healthy + damaged).
2-Group consecutive windows into blocks of size K  to simulate short periods of continuous monitoring.
3-Interleave healthy and damaged blocks to create a realistic data stream, either uniformly or randomly.
4-Load the pretrained TS-TCC model and extract context-vector embeddings for both the healthy training data and the streaming test data.
5-Fit a Mahalanobis model on healthy embeddings to learn the normal operating manifold of the structure.
6-Compute anomaly scores for each window in the stream and then aggregate them at the block level (using the mean or sum of the scores within each block).
7-Assign a label to each block using a rule such as:
        -any: a block is damaged if at least one window is damaged;
        -majority: a block is damaged if more than half of its windows are damaged.
8-Determine an anomaly threshold from the healthy training blocks .
9-Evaluate the online detection performance using block-level metrics such as:
Confusion Matrix, False Positive Rate (FPR), True Positive Rate (TPR), ROC-AUC, Average Precision (AP).
10-Visualize the results through confusion matrices and histograms of healthy and damaged block scores.